===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fr|en}} {{term|myriade|lang=fr}}, from {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{term|myriadis|lang=la}} (genitive of {{term|myrias|lang=la}}), from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|μυριάδος|sc=polytonic|tr=myriados|lang=grc}}, genitive of {{term|μυριάς|sc=polytonic|tr=myrias||number of 10,000|lang=grc}}, from {{term|μύριος|sc=polytonic|tr=myrios||numberless, countless, infinite|lang=grc}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈmɪɹiad/|/ˈmɪɹɪəd/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈmɪ.ɹi.æd/|/ˈmɪ.ɹi.əd/}}; {{X-SAMPA|/"mI.ri.{d/|/"mI.ri.@d/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}
# {{context|now|_|historical|lang=en}} [[ten|Ten]] [[thousand]]; 10,000 {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
# A countless [[number]] or [[multitude]] (of specified things) {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
#: ''Earth hosts a '''myriad''' of animals.''

====Usage notes====
Used as an adjective (see below), 'myriad' requires neither an article before it nor a preposition after. Because of this, some consider the usage described in sense 2 above, where 'myriad' acts as part of a nominal (or noun) group (that is, "a myriad of animals"), to be [[tautological]].

